sect2.para:
A clinician can minimize the likelihood of client surprise or discomfort during feedback (e. g., receiving unexpected outcomes) by conducting a person-centered interview with the end results in mind. Effective interviews provide information the clinician can use to generate an intake report that is informative and useful for treatment planning (see Segal & Hutchings,
            2007
         ). It can also be used to provide meaningful feedback, leaving the client with a better understanding of their presenting concerns. Throughout the interview, the clinician should explore symptom and behavior patterns in a way that can be referenced again during the feedback session (e. g., “Remember how you told me about [symptom or behavior pattern], well that is consistent with other people who are diagnosed with [DSM-5-TR disorder]”). When interviewing with the report and feedback in mind, the clinician strategically frames questions to elicit information that guides clients through the interview with sensitivity to potential outcomes. By skillfully integrating the client’s narratives and experiences into the interview process, clinicians ensure that diagnostic outcomes are not unexpected, but rather rooted in a comprehensive exploration of the client’s symptoms and behavioral patterns.
